 Como 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(b_{1}+b_{2}\right)\cdot h\cdot15
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}=5$
\end_inset

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}=2x+5$
\end_inset

, tenemos que
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t\right)=\frac{15}{2}\left(5+2x+5\right)h=15\left(5+x\right)h.
\]

\end_inset

Considerando la figura de la derecha, es claro, por semejanza de triángulos
 que
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x}{3}=\frac{h}{4}
\]

\end_inset

por lo cual 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(t\right)=15\left(5+\frac{3}{4}h\right)h=75h+\frac{45}{4}h^{2}\label{alb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

derivando (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) respecto a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
